The Archdeacon Brown Education Centre (ABEC), Port Harcourt, has said it will setup up a diagnostic centre where students with hearing difficulty and impaired vision. Managing Director of ABEC Group of Schools, Dr. Christie Toby disclosed this  in Port Harcourt while briefing newsmen as part of activities for the 20th anniversary of the school. Toby stated that the school, which was established in January 2000, has six different schools, including a special learning centre for physically-challenged children and a football academy. She described education as the only way to avoid poverty and instill discipline in the society, saying much will be achieved in the education sector if government could work together with private school operators. Toby said the 20th anniversary of the school is a celebration of the faithfulness of God on the private school, which run the Nigerian, British and American education curricular. She said: “We are 20 years old, we are excited, we are celebrating God’s faithfulness. We we look back, I seen the children, the girls. Some of them are married now and raising families. It is most gratifying. “We believe that there is still much to do; so much to contribute through quality education in our land. It is the only way we can eradicate poverty, it is the only way we can instill discipline.” Also speaking, former Rivers State Deputy Governor and ABEC Chairman, Alabo Gabriel Toby, commended the staff of the school for the successes recorded in the past 20 years by the school. Toby said: “We have a team of competent and dedicated heads of schools. The schools’ heads take the children as their own and they go beyond the call of duty. When we look back at our records, we are proud of what we have done. “We have zero tolerance for examination malpractices and no child passes through ABEC without being computer literate.”